info.name: Security Center Web SDK
info.description:
The Security Center Web SDK is an API that enables interaction with Genetec Security Center.  
For a comprehensive developer guide, please visit: [https://github.com/Genetec/DAP/wiki/Web-SDK-Developer-guide](https://github.com/Genetec/DAP/wiki/Web-SDK-Developer-guide).

request.description:
Adds a bookmark to a video sequence.

### What you should know

- A bookmark is an indicator of an event or incident that is used to mark a specific point in time in a recorded video sequence. A bookmark also contains a short text description that can be used to search for and review the video sequences at a later time.
- If a camera is not currently recording, adding a bookmark forces it to begin recording.
- If you add a bookmark to an exported video clip, the bookmark is only stored in the exported video clip and not the original archived video.

query.description:
- **camera:** Camera GUID or logical ID
- **timestamp:** Timestamp of bookmark

request.description: Delete a bookmark of a video sequence.

request.description:
Protect video footage from being deleted by the system when the Archiver’s disk space becomes full, or when its normal retention period has ended.

### What you should know

Video can be protected against deletion. Protection is applied to all video files needed to store the protected video sequence. Because no video file can be partially protected, the actual length of the protected video sequence depends on the granularity of the video files.

The Archiver cannot protect partial files, so you might protect a larger segment than the one you select.

query.description:
- **camera:** Camera GUID or logical ID
- **startTime:** Start time of the sequence to protect expressed in UTC 
- **endTime:** End time of the sequence to protect expressed in UTC
- **duration:** Duration for which the video should be protected

request.description:
Deletes a ghost camera.

A ghost camera is an entity used as a substitute camera. This entity is automatically created by the Archiver when video archives are detected for a camera whose definition has been deleted from the Directory, either accidentally or because the physical device no longer exists. Ghost cameras cannot be configured, and only exist so users can reference the video archive that would otherwise not be associated with any camera.

item.description:
Investigate events related to access control units, using the Access control unit events report.

 **What you should know**
 
 For example, you can use the Access control unit events report to see if any critical events relating to access control units occurred in the last week by searching for the specific event and setting the time range.
 
| Name               | Type       | Description                                           |
|--------------------|------------|-------------------------------------------------------|
| Timestamp          | DateTime   | The time (UTC) at which the event occurred.          |
| EventType          | EventType  | The EventType of the access control event.           |
| Unit               | Guid       | The unique identifier of the access control unit involved in the event. |
| Device             | Guid       | The unique identifier of the Device (Reader, InputDevice, etc...) involved in the event. |
| AP                 | Guid       | The unique identifier of the access point (DoorSide, etc...) involved in the event. |
| Source             | Guid       | The Guid of the source entity (DoorSide, Door, Area) involved in the event. |
| Credential         | Guid       | The unique identifier of the primary Credential involved in the event. |
| Cardholder         | Guid       | The unique identifier of the Cardholder involved in the event. |
| Credential2        | Guid       | The unique identifier of the second Credential involved in the event. |
| Timezone           | string     | The standard name of the Timezone in which the event occurred. |
| OccurrencePeriod   | int        | The integer value of OfflinePeriodType during which the event took place. |
| AccessPointGroup   | Guid       | The unique identifier of the access point group (Door, Area, etc...) involved in the event. |

item.description:
Investigate events related to visitors (access denied, first person in, last person out, antipassback violation, and so on), using the Visitor activities report.

**What you should know.**

You can see all the areas and doors that a visitor accessed during their stay. If you want to check for any critical events that occurred on your site in the last day in relation to visitors, you can set a time range for the report.

| Name             | Type       | Description                                           |
|------------------|------------|-------------------------------------------------------|
| Timestamp        | DateTime   | The time (UTC) at which the event occurred.          |
| EventType        | EventType  | The EventType of the access control event.           |
| Unit             | Guid       | The unique identifier of the access control unit involved in the event. |
| Device           | Guid       | The unique identifier of the Device (Reader, InputDevice, etc...) involved in the event. |
| AP               | Guid       | The unique identifier of the access point (DoorSide, etc...) involved in the event. |
| Source           | Guid       | The Guid of the source entity (DoorSide, Door, Area) involved in the event. |
| Credential       | Guid       | The unique identifier of the primary Credential involved in the event. |
| Cardholder       | Guid       | The unique identifier of the Cardholder involved in the event. |
| Credential2      | Guid       | The unique identifier of the second Credential involved in the event. |
| Timezone         | string     | The standard name of the Timezone in which the event occurred. |
| OccurrencePeriod | int        | The integer value of OfflinePeriodType during which the event took place. |
| AccessPointGroup | Guid       | The unique identifier of the access point group (Door, Area, etc...) involved in the event. |

item.description:
Investigate events related to zones (zone armed, zone disarmed, lock released, and so on), using the Zone activities report.

**What you should know**

For example, if you want to see all the activities that happened in a particular zone during a certain time period, you can select a zone, and a time range for the report. You can search for critical events only, by selecting the zone related events you are interested in (for example, door forced open).

| Name             | Type       | Description                                           |
|------------------|------------|-------------------------------------------------------|
| EventId          | int        | The unique database table identifier of the event occurrence. |
| TimeStampUtc     | DateTime   | The DateTime (UTC) at which the event occurred.     |
| TimeStampLocal   | DateTime   | The DateTime (local) at which the event occurred.   |
| TimeZoneId       | string     | The standard name of the Timezone in which the event occurred. |
| EventType        | int        | The integer value of the EventType associated with the event. |
| ZoneId           | Guid       | The unique identifier of the Zone entity involved in the event. |
| OfflinePeriod    | int        | The integer value of OccurrencePeriodType during which the event took place. |

item.description:
Find out which cardholders and visitors have been inside a selected area, and the total duration of their stay within a given date range.

**What you should know**

This report displays the total time spent in the selected area by each selected cardholder and visitor, for each day covered by the date range. For example, if something happened in an area two days ago, you can find out who was in that area during that day by selecting the area and the date range.
For the report to be accurate, the selected area must be fully secured, meaning that people should not be allowed to enter or exit the area without swiping their card. Readers should be installed on both sides of a door (no REX’s), and cardholders must pass through the door one by one (no tailgating). Turnstiles are often used for this purpose.

| SourceApplicationAsString | string | The name of the application that did the modification. |

| SourceApplicationType | enum | The Application type. |

| CustomFieldValueType | enum | The custom field value type. |
| AuditTrailModificationType | enum | The audit trail modification type. The enum is of type AuditTrailModificationType. |

| AuditTrailModificationSubTypes | string | Obsolete. Starting in SC 5.4, the value is always AuditTrailModificationSubTypes.None. |

| TriggerTime | DateTime | Time (UTC) at which the alarm was triggered in SecurityCenter. |
| AckedTime | DateTime | Time (UTC) at which the alarm was acked (DateTime.MinValue if not acked). |
| AckByGuid | Guid | Who acked the alarm, Guid.Empty if not acked. |
| CreationTime | DateTime | Time at which the alarm was created. TriggerTime != CreationTime when the alarm was created in a third-party system but was actually triggered in SC only X time afterward. |
| OfflinePeriod | OfflinePeriodType | The OfflinePeriodType during which the event took place. |
| AckReason | Int32 | The AckReason of the alarm. |
| ExternalInstanceID | Int32 | External instance ID (for a federated alarm). |
| InvestigatedByGuid | Guid | Who investigated the alarm, Guid.Empty if no investigation has been made. |
| InvestigatedTime | DateTime | Time (UTC) at which the alarm was investigated (DateTime.MinValue if never investigated). |
| State | byte | State of the alarm. |
| HasSourceCondition | boolean | The has source condition column name. |
| Priority | byte | Priority of the alarm. |
| DynamicContext | string | Dynamic Context of the alarm. |

request.description:
Reports on the configuration changes of entities in the system. Also indicates the user who made the changes. | Column # | Name | Type | Description | | --- | --- | --- | --- | | 0 | Id | int | The unique Id number. | | 1 | Guid | Guid | The Guid of the entity being audited. | | 2 | ModificationTimeStamp | DateTime | The modification time stamp (UTC). | | 3 | ModifiedBy | Guid | The Guid of the entity that modified the audited entity. | | 4 | SourceApplicationGuid | Guid | The Guid of the application entity that modified the audited entity. This
can be Config Tool, Security Desk, the SDK, etc. | | 5 | Name | string | The name of the audited entity. | | 6 | ModifiedByAsString | string | The name of the entity that modified the audited entity. | | 7 | SourceApplicationAsString | string | The name of the application that did the modification. | | 8 | Machine | string | The machine name. | | 9 | SourceApplicationType | enum | The enum is of type ApplicationType. | | 10 | OldValue | string | The old value. | | 11 | NewValue | string | The new value. | | 12 | CustomFieldId | Guid | The custom field id. This can be an empty Guid. | | 13 | CustomFieldName | string | The custom field name. This can be empty. | | 14 | CustomFieldValueType | enum | The custom field value type. The enum is of type
CustomFieldValueType. | | 15 | AuditTrailModificationType | enum | The audit trail modification type. The enum is of type
AuditTrailModificationType. | | 16 | Type | string | This represents the enum called EntityType. The value can be cast to an int
and then cast to an EntityType. | | 17 | Description | string | The description. | | 18 | AuditTrailModificationSubTypes | string | Obsolete. Starting in SC 5.4, the value is always
AuditTrailModificationSubTypes.None. | | 19 | Value | string | Value column represents some serialize meta information about the
audittrails |

View system health events related to selected entities.

| Name               | Type     | Description                                                               |
|--------------------|----------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| HealthEventId      | int      | The unique identifier for the health event.                              |
| EventSourceTypeId  | int      | The identifier for the event source type.                                |
| SourceEntityGuid   | Guid     | The unique identifier of the source entity associated with the event.    |
| EventDescription   | string   | A description of the event.                                              |
| MachineName        | string   | The name of the machine where the event occurred.                        |
| Timestamp          | DateTime | The UTC timestamp indicating when the event occurred.                    |
| SeverityId         | int      | The severity level of the event.                      |
| ErrorNumber        | int      | The error number associated with the event.                              |
| Occurence          | long     | The occurrence number of the event.                                      |
| ObserverEntity     | Guid     | The unique identifier of the observer entity monitoring the event.       |

item.description:
Monitor the health status and availability of system entities.

| Name                 | Type      | Description                                                           |
|----------------------|-----------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------|
| FailureCount         | int       | The number of failures recorded.                                      |
| RTPPacketLoss        | int       | The number of RTP packets lost.                                       |
| CalculationStatus    | int       | The status of the availability calculation.                          |
| SourceEntityGuid     | Guid      | The unique identifier of the source entity.                          |
| EventSourceType      | int       | The type of the event source.                                        |
| UnexpectedDowntime   | Timespan  | The amount of unexpected downtime.                                   |
| ExpectedDowntime     | Timespan  | The amount of expected downtime.                                     |
| Uptime               | Timespan  | The total uptime duration.                                           |

item.description:
View the properties of the video access control, and LPR units (firmware, IP address, time zone, and so on).

| Name                      | Type      | Description |
|---------------------------|-----------|-------------|
| UnitName                  | string    | Hardware unit name. |
| UnitType                  | enum (int) | Hardware unit type. Possible values: `19 = Unit`, `27 = LprUnit`, `36 = IntrusionUnit`, `39 = VideoUnit`. |
| UnitManufacturer          | string    | Unit manufacturer. |
| ProductType               | string    | Unit product type. |
| Role                      | GUID      | Role associated with the unit. |
| FirmwareVersion           | string    | Unit firmware version. |
| IpAddress                 | string    | Unit IP address. |
| PhysicalAddress           | string    | Unit MAC address. |
| TimeZone                  | string    | Unit time zone. |
| User                      | string    | Associated user. |
| PasswordStrength          | string    | Password strength. |
| UpgradeStatus             | string    | Firmware upgrade status. |
| NextUpgrade               | datetime  | Scheduled next upgrade. |
| UpgradeFailureReason      | enum (int) | Reason for upgrade failure. Possible values: `0 = None`, `1 = TransferFile`, `2 = InstallFile`, `3 = ExtractRPM`, `4 = WrongFile`, `5 = Downgrade`, `6 = UpgradePath`, `7 = UnknownFailure`, `8 = UnableStart`, `9 = UnitMovedOrDeleted`, `10 = ExtensionNotConnected`, `11 = VertXAdminPasswordRequired`, `12 = InvalidPassword`, `13 = NoDiskSpace`, `14 = DeprecatedVersion`. |
| State                     | string    | Unit current state. |
| PlatformVersion           | string    | Unit platform version. |
| Password                  | string    | Unit password (secure). |
| LastPasswordUpdate        | datetime  | Last password update. |
| Progress                  | string    | Upgrade progress. |
| ReaderType                | string    | Reader type. |
| ReaderEncryptionStatus    | enum (int) | Reader encryption status. Possible values: `0 = Unavailable`, `1 = No`, `2 = Yes`, `3 = Unknown`. |
| Related                   | string    | Related entity. |
| LicenseConsumption        | string    | License usage. |

In Security Center, intrusion detection refers to the detection of an intrusion into a secured area by an intrusion detection unit (hardware device).

Using the Parking zone activities report, you can track the parking zone-related events that occur between the time the vehicle's plate is read at the entrance and at the exit of the parking zone.

## What you should know

You can use the Parking zone activities report to audit the activities for a single license plate or to investigate cases where vehicle owner contests a parking ticket.

item.description:
View archiving role load information (number of cameras, disk space details, bandwidth and related statistics).

| Name                     | Type            | Description                                                          |
|--------------------------|-----------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------|
| RoleId                   | Guid            | The unique identifier of the archiver.                               |
| ServerId                 | Guid            | The unique identifier of the server associated with the role.        |
| ActiveCameras            | int             | The number of currently active cameras.                              |
| ArchivingCameras         | int             | The number of currently archiving cameras.                            |
| LoadPercent              | double          | The percent load on disk as UsedSpace / (UsedSpace + AvailableSpace) * 100 |
| ReceivingRate            | ulong           | The receiving rate.                                                  |
| WritingRate              | ulong           | The writing rate.                                                    |
| ArchivingSpan            | TimeSpan        | The archiving span.                                                  |
| AvailableSpace           | long            | The amount of available space on disk.                               |
| FreeSpace                | long            | The free space on disk.                                              |
| UsedSpace                | long            | The amount of used space on disk.                                    |
| NetworkTrafficIn         | ulong           | Network traffic in.                                                  |
| ComputerNetworkTrafficOut | ulong           | Network traffic out.                                                 |

item.description:
| Name                  | Type     | Description                                             |
|-----------------------|----------|---------------------------------------------------------|
| CameraGuid            | Guid     | The camera unique identifier.                           |
| ArchiveSourceGuid     | Guid     | The unique identifier of the source archiver.           |
| StartTime             | DateTime | The start time (UTC).                                   |
| EndTime               | DateTime | The end time (UTC).                                     |
| FilePath              | string   | The file path on the hard disk.                         |
| FileSize              | Decimal  | The file size (in bytes).                               |
| MetadataPath          | string   | The file path of the metadata.                          |
| ProtectionStatus      | uint     | The video protection state. The enum is of type VideoProtectionState. |
| InfiniteProtection    | Boolean  | True if the protection is infinite, otherwise false.    |
| Drive                 | string   | The hard drive location (C:\, D:\, etc).                |
| Error                 | uint     | The error code.                                         |
| ProtectionEndDateTime | DateTime | The date at which the protection ends (UTC).            |

item.name: Get thumbnail timestamps for one source

item.description:
Generate a thumbnail bitmap of an image captured by a camera at a specific timestamp.

| Name          | Type     | Description                                                                               |
|---------------|----------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Camera        | Guid     | The unique identifier of the camera entity to which the thumbnail belongs.               |
| Timestamp     | DateTime | The date and time of the thumbnail's creation.                                            |
| Thumbnail     | byte[]   | The thumbnail data. Use a `MemoryStream` to convert it to an image.                       |
| Context       | Guid     | The unique identifier of the context to which the thumbnail belongs, generally `Guid.Empty`. |
| LatestFrame   | DateTime | The date and time of the last frame if available; otherwise, `DateTime.MinValue`.         |

item.description:
API for managing areas.

In Security Center, an area entity represents a concept or a physical location (room, floor, building, site, and so on) used for grouping other entities in the system.

item.description:
API for managing cameras.

A camera entity represents a single video source in the system. The video source can either be an IP camera, or an analog camera that connects to the video encoder of a video unit. Multiple video streams can be generated from the same video source.

item.description:
API for managing camera sequences.

A camera sequence is an entity that defines a list of cameras that are displayed one after another in a rotating fashion within a single tile in Security Desk.

query.description:
- **formatId:** (GUID) The custom card format ID
- **valuesByFieldName:** (Key-Value Pairs): Field names and values for filtering, formatted as {{key1,value1},{key2,value2}}.

request.description:
**Parameters:**  
1. **`formatId`** (GUID): The unique ID of the custom card format. Example: `123e4567-e89b-12d3-a456-426614174000`.  
2. **`valuesByFieldName`** (Key-Value Pairs): Field names and values for filtering, formatted as `{{key1,value1},{key2,value2}}`.  
   - Example: `{{CardNumber,12345},{FacilityCode,678}}`.  

**Example Request:**  
`https://example.com/report/CredentialConfiguration?q=UniqueIds@CustomCredentialFormat(123e4567-e89b-12d3-a456-426614174000,{{CardNumber,12345},{FacilityCode,678}})`  

**Notes:**  
- `formatId` must match the configured card format ID in Security Center.  
- Keys in `valuesByFieldName` must align with field names in the custom card format.  

This retrieves credentials matching the specified format and field values.

A credential entity represents a proximity card, a biometrics template, or a PIN required to gain access to a secured area. A credential can only be assigned to one cardholder at a time.

item.description:
API for managing custom entity icons.

Entity icons graphically represent entity functions, acting as a quick visual hint when you are interacting with the entity tree.

You can change an entity's icon to match the entity's specific purpose (for example, a door entity that represents a turnstile or a parking gate).

item.description:
API for managing doors.

A door entity represents a physical barrier. Often, this is an actual door, but it could also be a gate, a turnstile, or any other controllable barrier. Each door has two sides named In and Out by default. Each side is an access point (entrance or exit) to a secured area.

API for creating, starting, stopping and view Macros.

Macros can be executed either manually or automatically. When automated, it is loaded as a background process and executes when a set of conditions are met.

You create macros by writing a program in C# using Security Center SDK, and then loading the program into Security Center.

request.description:
Get the privileges defined for a user, without influence from any user groups this user belongs to.

NOTE:
A privilege set at the Genetec.Sdk.Entities.User level overrides its inherited
user group privilege settings. In some situations, these could differ from what the Config Tool displays for the given user, because the Config Tool replaces undefined values with parent values if applicable. An example is when a new user is created without applying a privilege template, but belongs to a user group; this property will return Undefined values whereas the Config Tool will display the user group values.

request.description: Checkin a visitor.

query.description: **visitor:** Visitor GUID or logical ID

request.description:
Checkouts a visitor.

The checked-out visitor is removed from the visitor list, but remains available for investigation reports. The visitor’s information is also saved in the database, and can be used if the visitor returns.
If the visitor was assigned a credential, the credential status switches to Unassigned, and can be assigned to another visitor or cardholder. The credential is also removed from all access controllers it was synchronized with. This might take a few seconds.

item.description:
API for managing zones.

A zone is an entity that monitors a set of inputs and triggers events based on their combined states. These events can be used to control output relays.

query.description: **entity:** Entity GUID or logical ID

item.description:
Entities are the basic building blocks of Security Center. Everything that requires configuration is represented by an entity. An entity can represent a physical device, such as a camera or a door, or an abstract concept, such as an alarm, a schedule, a user, a role, a plugin, or an add-on.

The /entity endpoint has a q parameter q=entity={{entity}} that needs to be replaced with a set of actions.

For example, to access an entity, use /entity?q={query}, where {query} can be replaced with a comma-separated list of action tags.

Actions are used to interact with Security Center SDK entities.  
You can use actions to set or get the value of a property, add or remove items from a collection property, and more.

To set the value of a property, use syntax like "Name=John Smith" or "ActivationMode=RelativeDeactivation(6.00:00:00)".


To add or remove items from a collection property, use @ to add, - to remove, and \* to clear the collection.  
For example, "Credentials@1d5eacc8df6947b1922f1d5661eae3b6@6f756ca9-c7db-48cb-8135-f8913fb1edaa" adds two GUIDs to a collection property.

item.name: Open a real time event stream

request.description:
Opens the HTTP streaming connection.

HTTP Streaming is a push-style data transfer technique that allows a web server to continuously send data to a client over a single HTTP connection that remains open indefinitely.

With HTTP Streaming, the server is configured to hold on to a specific request from a client and keep the response open so that it can push data through it. When updates pertaining to the request are available server side, the server sends a response through the request-response channel, and only closes the connection when explicitly told to do so.

In such a manner, a client can listen for updates from the server and receive them instantly with none of the overhead associated with HTTP headers and the opening/closing of connections. It also eliminates the need for polling.

To achieve an indefinite response, the server respond to client requests by specifying Transfer Encoding: chunked in the header.

This sets up a persistent connection from server to client and allows the server to send response data in chunks of newline-delimited strings.  
These chunks of data can then be received and processed on-the-fly by the client.

response.name: Open a real time event stream

item.description:
## Custom events

A custom event is an event added after the initial system installation.  
Events defined at system installation are called system events.  
Custom events can be user-defined or automatically added through plugin installations.  
Unlike system events, custom events can be renamed and deleted.

### How to create a custom event

To create a custom event, send the following POST request:

``` http
POST /entity?q=entity=00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000007,CustomEvents.Add({eventId},{name},{entityType})

 ```

Simply replace {eventId} with the unique ID of the custom event, {name} with the name of the custom event, and {entityType} with the entity type of the source of the custom event.

**NOTE: Both {eventId} and {eventName} must be unique.**

### How to delete a custom event

To delete a custom event, send the following POST request:

``` http
POST /entity?q=entity=00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000007,CustomEvents-{eventId}

 ```

Simply replace {eventId} with the ID of the custom event you wish to delete.

### How to retrieve existing custom events

To retrieve all existing custom events, send the following GET request:

``` http
GET /entity?q=entity=00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000007,CustomEvents

 ```

### How to identify the custom events that an entity can raise

To list the supported custom events of an entity, send the following GET request:

``` http
GET /entity?q=entity={entity},SupportedCustomEvents

 ```

Simply replace {entity} with either the GUID or the logical ID of an entity.

Here is an example of the response:

``` json
{
    "Rsp": {
        "Status": "Ok",
        "Result": {
            "SupportedCustomEvents": [
                {
                    "Id": 1,
                    "LocalCustomEvent": true,
                    "Name": "Cardholder custom event",
                    "SourceEntityType": "Cardholder",
                    "Owner": "00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000"
                }
            ]
        }
    }
}

 ```

### How to raise a custom event

To raise a custom event, send the following POST request:

``` http
POST /events/RaiseCustomEvent/{eventId}/{entityId}/{message}

 ```

Simply replace {eventId} with the ID of the custom event, {entityId} with the GUID of the custom event source entity, and optionally {message} with a custom message.

item.description:
In the context of Security Center, an event indicates the occurrence of an activity or incident, such as access denied to a cardholder or motion detected on a camera.  
Events are automatically logged in Security Center.  
Every event has an entity as its main focus, called the event source.

### How to monitor events in real-time

To monitor events, you must first subscribe to one or more events.  
You can subscribe to events raised by specific entities or raised by all entities.

To subscribe to events from a specific entity, send the following GET request:

``` http
GET /events/subscribe?q=event({source},{eventType})

 ```

Simply replace {source} with either the GUID or the logical ID of an entity to receive events for that specific entity.

To subscribe to events from all entities of a given type, send the following GET request:

``` http
GET /events/subscribe?q=event({entityType},{eventType})

 ```

Simply replace {entityType} with the type of entity you wish to recieve event from.

:bulb: **You can combine multiple subscriptions into a single request.**

``` http
POST /events/subscribe?q=event({source1},{eventType1}),event({source2},{eventType2}),event({source3},{eventType3})

 ```

:warning: **Subscribing to specific custom events only is not supported.**

Similarly, to unsubscribe, send the following GET request:

``` http
GET /events/unsubscribe?q=event({source},{eventType})

 ```

To retrieve the list of all event subscriptions, send the following GET request:

``` http
GET /events/subscribed

 ```

Here is an example of the response:

``` json
{
    "Rsp": {
        "Status": "Ok",
        "Result": [
            {
                "EventType": "CameraMotion",
                "Entities": [
                    "00000001-0000-babe-0000-7a825fe95e6d",
                    "00000001-0000-babe-0000-07f70b10c103",
                    "4bf63e7e-4973-4d7f-8437-74e742a6a856",
                    "00000001-0000-babe-0000-6ec222f7f57e",
                    "00000001-0000-babe-0000-c5bf77d09e2a",
                    "00000001-0000-babe-0000-02e7a5cd8df8",
                    "00000001-0000-babe-0000-51b6928e57d4",
                    "00000001-0000-babe-0000-201b16db264a"
                ]
            },
            {
                "EventType": "AccessGranted",
                "Entities": [
                    "bb29039d-aa1a-4c35-aa1e-4f89c6006b6d"
                ]
            }
        ]
    }
}

 ```

To open the HTTP events stream, send the following GET request:

``` http
GET /events/

 ```

The request will then be redirected to the streaming port (default is 4591)

### How does HTTP event streaming work

Here is a general overview of how the web SDK sends real-time events:

The client initiates an HTTP connection to the server using a standard HTTP GET request.

The server redirects the request to the streaming port and responds with an HTTP response that includes the Content-Type: multipart/mixed header, specifying the boundary string (--GENETECBOUNDARY).  
This indicates that the server will be sending a multipart stream of events.

The server starts streaming individual event messages as separate parts of the multipart response.  
Each event is encapsulated within a part and separated by the specified boundary.

Each event part typically includes content specific to the event, such as the event type, timestamp, and event data.

The server continues streaming events as long as the connection remains open.  
New events are sent by the server as soon as they occur, allowing for real-time delivery of events to the client.

The client receives the event parts one by one as they are streamed.  
The client can process each event as it arrives, react to the event data, and take appropriate actions.  
It's worth noting that the client needs to handle the parsing and extraction of individual event parts based on the specified boundary.

### How to enable alarm monitoring

When alarm monitoring is enabled, alarms will also be sent to the event stream.

:warning: **Monitoring specific alarms is not supported.**

To enable alarm monitoring, send the following POST request:

``` http
POST /events/alarmMonitoring/on

 ```

To disable alarm monitoring, send the following POST request:

``` http
POST /events/alarmMonitoring/off

 ```

### How to raise an event

To raise a event, send the following POST request:

``` http
POST /events/RaiseEvent/{eventType}/{entityId}

 ```

Simply replace {eventType} with the type of the event and {entityId} with the GUID of the event source entity.

:warning: **Specifying the event timestamp is not currently supported.**

item.description:
An event-to-action links an action to an event. For example, you can configure Security Center to trigger an alarm when a door is forced open.

An action is a user-programmable function that can be triggered as an automatic response to an event, such as door held open for too long or object left unattended, or that can be executed according to a specific time table.
